  <rdf:Description rdf:about="https://w3id.org/ocd#Symmetry_Intrusive_Thought">
    <rdfs:comment>The concept of symmetry-related obsessions can be elucidated by viewing it through the lens of Y-BOCS. These obsessions often entail an intense preoccupation with symmetry and order in one's surroundings. Individuals with symmetry-related obsessions may engage in rituals and behaviors aimed at creating a sense of balance, and these behaviors may sometimes involve magical thinking. For instance, someone with symmetry-related thoughts might believe that unless objects are arranged in a particular way, harm may come to others. This is an example of symmetry-related obsessions accompanied by magical thinking. On the other hand, some individuals experience symmetry-related obsessions without the presence of magical thinking. These thoughts can be associated with distress, time-consuming rituals, and functional impairment, hence, they categorize as intrusive.</rdfs:comment>
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class"/>
    <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://w3id.org/ocd#Intrusive_Thoughts"/>
  </rdf:Description>
